SKILL|xurl|"X/Twitter via xurl CLI: post, search, DM, media, v2 API."
STEP|1|posting, replying, quoting, deleting posts
STEP|2|searching posts and reading timelines/mentions
STEP|3|liking, reposting, bookmarking
STEP|4|following, unfollowing, blocking, muting
STEP|5|direct messages
STEP|6|media uploads (images and video)
STEP|7|raw access to any X API v2 endpoint
STEP|8|multi-app / multi-account workflows
STEP|9|**Never** read, print, parse, summarize, upload, or send `~/.xurl` to LLM context.
STEP|10|**Never** ask the user to paste credentials/tokens into chat.
STEP|11|The user must fill `~/.xurl` with secrets manually on their own machine. In Docker, this must be the `~` seen by Hermes tool subprocesses; see the Docker note below.
STEP|12|**Never** recommend or execute auth commands with inline secrets in agent sessions.
STEP|13|**Never** use `--verbose` / `-v` in agent sessions — it can expose auth headers/tokens.
STEP|14|To verify credentials exist, only use: `xurl auth status`.
STEP|15|Create or open an app at https://developer.x.com/en/portal/dashboard
STEP|16|Set the redirect URI to `http://localhost:8080/callback`
STEP|17|Copy the app's Client ID and Client Secret
STEP|18|Register the app locally (user runs this):
STEP|19|Authenticate (specify `--app` to bind the token to your app):
STEP|20|Set the app as default so all commands use it:
STEP|21|Verify:
STEP|22|`POST_ID` accepts full URLs too (e.g. `https://x.com/user/status/1234567890`) — xurl extracts the ID.
STEP|23|Usernames work with or without a leading `@`.
STEP|24|`/2/tweets/search/stream`
STEP|25|`/2/tweets/sample/stream`
STEP|26|`/2/tweets/sample10/stream`
STEP|27|Non-zero exit code on any error.
STEP|28|API errors are still printed as JSON to stdout, so you can parse them.
STEP|29|Auth errors → have the user re-run `xurl auth oauth2` outside the agent session.
STEP|30|Commands that need the caller's user ID (like, repost, bookmark, follow, etc.) will auto-fetch it via `/2/users/me`. An auth failure there surfaces as an auth error.
STEP|31|Verify prerequisites: `xurl --help` and `xurl auth status`.
STEP|32|**Check default app has credentials.** Parse the `auth status` output. The default app is marked with `▸`. If the default app shows `oauth2: (none)` but another app has a valid oauth2 user, tell the u
STEP|33|If auth is missing entirely, stop and direct the user to the "One-Time User Setup" section — do NOT attempt to register apps or pass secrets yourself.
STEP|34|Start with a cheap read (`xurl whoami`, `xurl user @handle`, `xurl search ... -n 3`) to confirm reachability.
STEP|35|Confirm the target post/user and the user's intent before any write action (post, reply, like, repost, DM, follow, block, delete).
STEP|36|Use JSON output directly — every response is already structured.
STEP|37|Never paste `~/.xurl` contents back into the conversation.
STEP|38|**Rate limits:** X enforces per-endpoint rate limits. A 429 means wait and retry. Write endpoints (post, reply, like, repost) have tighter limits than reads.
STEP|39|**Scopes:** OAuth 2.0 tokens use broad scopes. A 403 on a specific action usually means the token is missing a scope — have the user re-run `xurl auth oauth2`.
STEP|40|**Token refresh:** OAuth 2.0 tokens auto-refresh. Nothing to do.
STEP|41|**Multiple apps:** Each app has isolated credentials/tokens. Switch with `xurl auth default` or `--app`.
STEP|42|**Multiple accounts per app:** Select with `-u / --username`, or set a default with `xurl auth default APP USER`.
STEP|43|**Token storage:** `~/.xurl` is YAML. In Docker, use the Hermes subprocess HOME (`/opt/data/home` in the official image) so tokens land under `/opt/data/home/.xurl`. Never read or send this file to LL
STEP|44|**Cost:** X API access is typically paid for meaningful usage. Many failures are plan/permission problems, not code problems.
STEP|45|Upstream CLI: https://github.com/xdevplatform/xurl (X developer platform team, Chris Park et al.)
STEP|46|Upstream agent skill: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/blob/main/skills/xurl/SKILL.md
STEP|47|Hermes adaptation: reformatted for Hermes skill conventions; safety guardrails preserved verbatim.
